Technical Report

#Abstract: Our project investigated the question of what variables contribute and to what extent do they contribute to predicting regular season wins for NBA teams. For this we brainstormed potential variables and imported them using Basketball Reference. These variables correspond to team chemistry, history, and coaching. From here we eliminated variables to fit a model that follows our regression assumptions and our variables have meaningful coefficients. Our final equation and best fitted model used 5 explantory variables.

#Introduction: This project attempts to bring qualitative and statistical undertstanding to what contributes to basketball wins. This question can help guide how NBA organizations are managed to contribute to success in basketball and financially. Our project helped reveal what variables can useful in predicting wins, and while we only have a small sample of variables we could repeat this process with many more variables to obtain a better model. Specfically regarding the model we whittled our variables down to coachWinPct, MVP, combinbedYrs, div, and ROTY. These variables fit the model assumptions and gave the best p-value and \(R^2\). We have discovered some useful variables, but to improve the model we would need to account for a lot more characteristics of team to make it more accurate. Our model gives detects useful information, but is to simplistic to accurately describe an arbitrary season.

#Results: The equation for our model is \(Wins = -0.45543 + coachWinPct*0.55470 + MVP*3.22367 + combinedYrs*0.10617 + div*0.50184 + ROTY*5.69019\). After intially fitting the model, conf had a negative coefficient which does not make sense as conference championships should not be associated with less wins. As our model has a decent \(R^2\) value (0.5104 ) and a significant p-value (0.0003523), so this model has statistical significant can give useful information within its context. The variables listed in order of p-value significance is coachWinPct, div, ROTY, combinedyrs, and MVP. We note here that MVP had a poor individual p-value of 59% and combinedYrs, div, and ROTY had poor but justifiable p-values below 15%. We can easily summarize which variable had the biggest impact as each is subjective to its varying input size; however, all of our variables have a coefficent that makes sense in the context of basketball. It is also important to note that wins are an integer number so we need to round up or down to the nearest whole number when making a prediction. It is also interesting that ROTY had a higher impact than MVP, but this makes sense because only three have former MVP winners since the Houston Rockets have two and Stephen Curry won the award back to back years. Whereas, 10 teams had a player win Rookie of the Year. Addditioanlly, the Regular Seasons wins have a lower bound of 0 and an upper bound of 82 since 82 games are played in a season. This should be taken into account when giving an example. Now we will interpret every coefficient in context. coachWinPct: For every percentage increase in coaching wins capped at 100, there is an expected win increase of 0.5547. MVP: If a team has a player whom has won MVP in the last five seasons, there is an expected win increase of 3.22367 combinedYrs: For every year of experience in the league per player on a team corresponds a win increase of 0.10617.
div: For every division win for a team there is an expected win increase of 0.50184.
ROTY: If a team has had a ROTY from the past 10 seasons they are expected win an extra 5.69019 games.

#Conclusion: Our project attempted to find variables to predict NBA regular season wins and incorporate these variables into a model. Based on our model we can conclude that the variables that fit best into a model are coachWinPct, MVP, combinedYrs, div, and ROTY. This model is useful for providing some insight on how much the variables can affect a teams number of wins in a season; however, this should not be a primary indicator for how many wins a team gets. Other on the court and qualitative factors can have larger impacts such as player fits, injuries, and player relationships. To improve this aspect of the model, we could attempt to quantify many of these concepts and encode them as variables and eliminate variables from the top; however, this would be most beneficial with insider analysis from those closest to the league as much of this information could be subjective. This notion corresponds mainly to our variables but also to our model. Ultimately, this model gives us an idea of how much each variables corresponds to wins in comparison to each other.
